{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 The employer argued that it did not owe the wife a duty. The reviewing court agreed, finding as an initial matter that the relevant time period began in 1942 when the employee/husband went to work in a refinery, and ended in 1972, when he began working in an air-conditioned tool room. In 1972, even though there were still mixed messages from the medical and scientific community on the risks associated with asbestos exposure, the Occupational Health and Safety Administration (OSHA) prohibited employers from allowing workers who had been exposed to asbestos to wear their work clothes home. Based on the evidence introduced during the trial, the employer did not become aware of the take-home risk of asbestos exposure until that point. As a result of the OSHA regulations, the employer was put on notice in 1972, after the employee/husband started working in the air-conditioned tool room, that asbestos posed a risk to persons, such as employee families, who were never on the employer's premises. It followed that in 1972 the risk to the wife of contracting a serious illness became foreseeable, triggering, for the first time, a duty to protect her and persons similarly situated.}
